node.text:
💧 With Hubble data, astronomers found evidence of water vapor in the atmosphere of Jupiter’s moon Ganymede!

This is an ice-covered world that might hold more water than all of Earth’s oceans combined… but Ganymede’s oceans exist below a 100-mile-thick, icy crust.

This atmospheric water vapor was formed in a process called sublimation, when a solid turns directly into a gas (ice ➡️ water vapor).

Find out more about this discovery at the link in our bio!

#NASA #Hubble #video #Jupiter #Ganymede #moon #planet #space #solarsystem #water #news

node.title: Hubble Finds Evidence of Water Vapor at Jupiter’s Moon Ganymede

“That’s one of the benefits of a program that’s been running for over 30 years: the incredible amount of experience and expertise.”

Their efforts helped ensure that Hubble’s exploration of the universe is far from over. Read more at the link in our bio!

Dark matter is the “invisible glue” that holds the universe together.

All galaxies seem to be dominated by it, but Hubble observations of an oddball galaxy lacking dark matter are challenging theories of galaxy formation.

Learn more about this cosmic mystery at the link in our bio!

A magnetic force to be reckoned with 🧲✨

This stunning galaxy called NGC 1275 contains red filaments near its center which are shaped by a strong magnetic field. These lacy structures are fine threads of gas up to 20,000 light-years long and 200 light-years wide.

Observing these filaments allows astronomers to estimate the strength of the magnetic field and how these filaments maintain their structure despite gravitational forces.

Stars can be friends too! ✨

In this Hubble image, you're seeing a globular star cluster called Caldwell 87. Located around 50,000 light-years away from Earth, these close-knit stars are gravitationally bound to one another.

But like any group of friends, not every cluster is the same, and scientists are using observations of clusters like Caldwell 87 to learn more about the stars' ages and chemical makeup.

🌌 In the short span of a human life, it’s rare for us to witness an astronomical process unfold – for example, it can take millions of years for a rocky planet to form.

But stunning time-lapse videos released #OTD 10 years ago gave us a glimpse of spectacular cosmic events!

With 14 years of Hubble observations, a team of scientists put together movies that showed young stars releasing gas in supersonic jets that tear through interstellar environments.

Analyzing these stars has helped us learn more about the final stages of a star's birth, offering a peek at how our own Sun might have behaved 4.5 billion years ago.

node.text:
How many galaxies do you think are in the center of this image?

Looks can be deceiving 😲

In reality, only two galaxies and one quasar appear in the middle of this incredible #HubbleFriday view.

Something called gravitational lensing occurs when a celestial object with an enormous amount of mass – such as the pair of galaxies at the image’s center – causes the fabric of space to warp.

When light from a distant object travels through that gravitationally warped space, it is magnified and bent around the huge mass. This allows humans here on Earth to observe multiple, magnified images of the faraway source. The quasar in this image actually lies farther away from Earth than the pair of galaxies.

The galaxy pair’s enormous mass bent and magnified the light from the distant quasar, giving the incredible appearance that the galaxies are surrounded by four quasars – when in reality, a single quasar lies far beyond them!

Find out more at the link in our bio.

Image credits: ESA/Hubble & NASA, T. Treu; Acknowledgment: J. Schmidt

A blast from the past! 🕐

Using Hubble, astronomers studied a comet named ATLAS and found that it may be a broken-off piece of a comet that might’ve been visible about 5,000 years ago!

How do we know that? ATLAS follows the same orbital “railroad track” as that of a comet seen in 1844, which means those two comets are probably siblings from a “parent” comet that broke apart many centuries earlier.

ATLAS disintegrated into small, icy pieces in mid-2020 and its surviving sibling won’t return until the 50th century.
